<h2>POPULATING THE DATA</h2>

<p>So far we've talked about accessing data from a Cassandra instance that has already been populated with the data we need. But how do we get it in there in the first place? The answer to this question is a two-step process; first we create the relevant structures within Cassandra and then we use our Python tools to gather and add the actual data.</p>

<p>My preferred tool for managing my Cassandra instance is the pycassaShell that comes with Pycassa. This tool makes it's easy to create the column families and indexes we've been working with:</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
